I"q<p>Phenomenal representations can be seen as a special type of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mental-representations-connect-internal-with-external-state">mental representations</a>. Whereas <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mental-representations-connect-internal-with-external-state">mental representations</a> are merely <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/tools-for-thought-interface-users-with-knowledge">tools</a>, phenomenal representation is self-conscious usage of those tools, avoiding homoncular explanations by pointing to a model of self-consciousness. In <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/conscious-unconscious-divide-has-edge-cases">blindsight</a>, some <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mental-representations-connect-internal-with-external-state">mental representations</a> canâ€™t turn into phenomenal ones.</p>
